The one village, one shrine concept was initially shelved due to lack of funds, but in 1943 the prefecture applied to the national government for grants to restore the [[eight Ryukyu shrines]]. In addition, five new shrines were designated as prefectural shrines {{Refn|{{ill|Futemma-gū|ja|沖宮}} ({{ill|Futemma-gū|ja|沖宮}}), {{ill|Saiba Shrine|ja|斎場神社}} ({{ill|Seifa Utaki|ja|斎場御嶽}}), {{ill|Hokuzan Shrine|ja|北山神社}} ({{ill|Nakijin Castle|ja|今帰仁城}}), {{ill|Miyako Shrine|ja|宮古神社}}, and {{ill|Yaeyama Shrine|ja|八重山神社}} (possibly {{ill|Ōishigaki Utaki|ja|大石垣御嶽}}){{sfn|後田多敦ほか|2020|pp=25-28}} make up the five shrines{{sfn|加治順人|2018|pp=53-55}}.|group=注釈}}, and a plan was drawn up to consolidate the more than 900 Utaki shrines into 60 village shrines and 150 subordinate shrines. {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} Among the utaki that have been converted into shrines are {{ill|10=ja|11=白銀堂|Shirogane-do|8=en}} in {{ill|10=ja|11=糸満市|Itoman|8=en}}, {{ill|10=ja|11=月代宮|Tsukishiro-gu Shrine|8=en}} in {{ill|10=ja|11=南城市|Sashiki|8=en}}, {{ill|10=ja|11=佐敷町_(沖縄県)|Nanjō|8=en}},  {{ill|10=ja|11=惣慶宮|Sōkei-gu Shrine|8=en}} and {{ill|10=ja|11=泡瀬神社|Awase Shrine|8=en}} in {{ill|10=ja|11=宜野座村|Ginoza village|8=en}}, {{ill|10=ja|11=新里宮|Shinzato-gu Shrine|8=en}} in {{ill|10=ja|11=本部町|Motobu, Okinawa|fr|Motobu|zh|本部町|8=en}},  {{ill|10=ja|11=十山神社|Toyama Shrine|8=en}} in {{ill|10=ja|11=与那国町|Yonaguni town|8=en}}, and {{ill|10=ja|11=白浜神社 (竹富町)|Shirahama-jinja Shrine|8=en}} on {{ill|Iriomote Island|8=en}} . {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} In addition, training seminars for {{ill|10=ja|11=ノロ|Noro (priestess)|lt=Noro|8=en}} recommended by local government leaders were held at Gokoku Shrines and other locations in an attempt to fill the shortage of priests by switching them from Noro to other priests. {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} {{Refn|In contrast, {{ill|Yuta|ja|ユタ}} were being targeted for regulation during the same period for "misleading the public."{{sfn|加治順人|2018|pp=55-57}}。|group=注釈}} However, the four-year plan, one village, one company, was thwarted by the worsening war situation. {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} Furthermore, the Ministry of Home Affairs documents state that there were ten shrines in Okinawa as of 1938 (Showa 13) {{Sfn|影山正治|1972}}, but Sueyasu Daiko (1992) claims that by the end of the war the number of shrines was as high as 227 {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} .


