* {{ill|Sueyoshi-gū|ja|末吉宮|12=draft}}}}, and a plan was proposed to develop the local utaki shrines into shrines. This idea was first proposed around 1939, and was featured in a newspaper article on August 27, 1940 (Showa 15) as "One Village, One Company" {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} .The one village, one shrine concept was initially shelved due to lack of funds, but in 1943 the prefecture applied to the national government for grants to restore the [[eight Ryukyu shrines]]. In addition, five new shrines were designated as prefectural shrines {{Refn|{{ill|Futemma-gū|ja|普天満宮|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sefa-utaki|lt=Saiba Shrine|ja|斎場神社|12=draft}} ({{ill|Sefa-utaki|ja|斎場御嶽|12=draft}}), {{ill|Nakijin Castle|lt=Hokuzan Shrine|ja|北山神社|12=draft}} ({{ill|Nakijin Castle|ja|今帰仁城|12=draft}}), {{ill|Miyako Shrine|ja|宮古神社|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Yaeyama Shrine|ja|八重山神社|12=draft}} (possibly {{ill|Ōishigaki Utaki|ja|大石垣御嶽|12=draft}}){{sfn|後田多敦ほか|2020|pp=25-28}} make up the five shrines{{sfn|加治順人|2018|pp=53-55}}.|group=注釈}}, and a plan was drawn up to consolidate the more than 900 Utaki shrines into 60 village shrines and 150 subordinate shrines. {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} Among the utaki that have been converted into shrines are {{ill|Shirogane-do|8=en|10=ja|11=白銀堂|12=draft}} in {{ill|Itoman|8=en|10=ja|11=糸満市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tsukishiro-gu Shrine|8=en|10=ja|11=月代宮|12=draft}} in {{ill|Sashiki|8=en|10=ja|11=南城市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nanjō|8=en|10=ja|11=佐敷町_(沖縄県)|12=draft}},  {{ill|Sōkei-gu Shrine|8=en|10=ja|11=惣慶宮|12=draft}} and {{ill|Awase Shrine|8=en|10=ja|11=泡瀬神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Ginoza village|8=en|10=ja|11=宜野座村|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shinzato-gu Shrine|8=en|10=ja|11=新里宮|12=draft}} in {{ill|Motobu, Okinawa|fr|Motobu|zh|本部町|8=en|10=ja|11=本部町|12=draft}},  {{ill|Toyama Shrine|8=en|10=ja|11=十山神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Yonaguni town|8=en|10=ja|11=与那国町|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Shirahama-jinja Shrine|8=en|10=ja|11=白浜神社 (竹富町)|12=draft}} on {{ill|Iriomote Island|8=en}} . {{Sfn|加治順人|2018|12=draft}} In addition, training seminars for {{ill|Noro (priestess)|8=en|10=ja|11=ノロ|lt=Noro|12=draft}} recommended by local government leaders were held at Gokoku Shrines and other locations in an attempt to fill the shortage of priests by switching them from Noro to other priests. {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} {{Refn|In contrast, {{ill|Yuta|ja|ユタ|12=draft}} were being targeted for regulation during the same period for "misleading the public."{{sfn|加治順人|2018|pp=55-57}}。|group=注釈}}
 However, the four-year plan, one village, one company, was thwarted by the worsening war situation. {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} Furthermore, the Ministry of Home Affairs documents state that there were ten shrines in Okinawa as of 1938 (Showa 13) {{Sfn|影山正治|1972}}, but Sueyasu Daiko (1992) claims that by the end of the war the number of shrines was as high as 227 {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}} .
Many shrines were destroyed and fell into disrepair following {{ill|Battle of Okinawa|the Battle of Okinawa|8=en|12=draft}} . However, it is not clear whether all of these were the result of U.S. military attacks. For example, in photographs taken by the U.S. military immediately after the Battle of Okinawa, Gokoku Shrine was still standing, although there was a large hole in the roof of the worship hall. However, Nagamine Ushio (1953) {{Refn|"The Past, Present, and Future of Gokoku Shrine," The Journey of Okinawa Prefecture Gokoku Shrine, pp. 119-128 (originally published in 1953)
<!--「護國神社の今昔と将来」『沖縄県護国神社のあゆみ』pp. 119-128（初出は 1953 年）-->|group=注釈}}
 {{Sfn|加治順人|2018}}
testified that "when I saw it in 1946, the torii gate was still there, but a few years later it was gone without a trace," suggesting that it may have been dismantled and used as building materials during the postwar reconstruction period. 
