'''Toyama Shrine''' (十山神社, ''Tōyama Jinja'') is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in the {{ill|Sonai (Yonaguni)|ja|祖納|qq=draft|qq=draft}} district of {{ill|Yonaguni, Okinawa|ja|与那国町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yaeyama District, Okinawa|ja|八重山郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan.

It is the westernmost shrine in Japan. The shrine is also known by its alternative name, '''Toyama Utaki''' (十山御嶽, ''Toyama Ugan'').

This shrine represents a unique fusion of {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Utaki (Okinawa)|lt=Utaki|ja|御嶽|1=Utaki|2=ja|3=御嶽 (沖縄)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} faith of the {{ill|Yaeyama Islands|ja|八重山諸島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, maintaining distinctive traditions. The shrine’s annual {{ill|豊年祭|ja|豊年祭|1=Hōnensai|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Harvest Festival) is held on {{ill|June 26 (lunar calendar)|ja|6月26日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and includes a sacred {{ill|Tug-of-war|ja|綱引き|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ritual.
==Excerpt from [[History of Shinto shrines in Okinawa]]==

